It hath Arteries in the Neck from the carotides;
in the thorax from the Intercotals, and in the abdomen
from the ramus coeliacus coronarius.

There are Nerves and Lympheducts that pas
into the Teticles together with thee Vaa praeparantia;
of which in the next Chapter.

It is neither bony, as in a Dog, Fox, Wolf;
nor grily nor flehy; but is framed of uch a ubtance
as might admit of ditention and relaxation.

Its ubtance is whitih,Subtance. nervous or rather membranous;
dene and compact in Virgins, but in
Women with Child a little pongy and oft.

As for its Veels:Veins. Veins and Arteries it hath
from thoe called Mammariae internae,
                     Arteries. but mall;
and Veins beides from Vena ine pari.

It is placed in the highet region,Its eat. mot fit for
the organs of the Senes, but chiefly for the Eyes;
for they ought to be placed there as in a Watch-tower:
and beides having but oft Nerves which


could not endure a long paage, it was requiite
that the Brain hould be near them.

The Mediana is alo double, Profunda and ubcutanea;
both which run by many twigs through
the Mucles of the Cubit to the Hand and Fingers.

